botMessages.message: In order to guarantee that 401(k) plans are used for retirement, the IRS imposes age limits on specific accounts.
Since you are under 59 ½ years of age, the option to withdrawal money from your account is if you hold a rollover balance in your current plan.
You would first need to confirm that your plan allows for hardship withdrawals. You can check that information by:

1) From the main navigation menu on the left side, select Overview. 2)Scroll down to Distributions 3) Under the feature column, you will see Hardship Withdrawals. 4) Under the your plan column, find the coinciding row with Hardship Withdrawals to confirm

If your plan permits Hardship Withdrawals and you qualify to make this type of withdrawal, you would initiate this request by going to the main navigation menu on the left hand side of the screen and select the Withdraw/Rollover Out option.
From there, you would walk through the process of applying for a Hardship Withdrawal.
Did that answer your question?

botMessages.message: The IRS imposes age limits on retirement accounts because these plans are intended only for retirement.
Since you are under age 59 1/2, you can only withdraw money from your account if you hold a rollover balance in your current plan from another retirement account or Traditional IRA.

botMessages.message: The maximum loan amount available to borrow is the lesser of $50,000 (minus the highest outstanding loan balance in the last 12 months) or 50% of your vested account balance.
The minimum vested amount that you can have in your account to qualify for a loan is $2,000.
For more information about the loan process, please see our Loan Frequently Asked Questions: https://www.myubiquity.com/whitepaper/loan-faq/.​

botMessages.message: Form 1099-R reports the withdrawal of retirement benefits.
Did that answer your question?

Withdrawals out of your Ubiquity account:​
If you took a withdrawal, cash or rollover you should have received a 1099-R form in the mail by January 31st in the following year that the withdrawal occurred.
Loans that are current and not considered in default will not be reported and do not require a 1099-R​.
Loans that were offset at the time of your distribution and considered taxable income do require a 1099-R.

Loans that ARE NOT current due to termination of employment or missed payments, may require a 1099-R. Note, the Cares Act allowed for some loan payments to be deferred in 2020, so even if your loan is not current, a 1099-R may not be required.
Please Chat with an agent or call us at 855.401.4357, Option 2, Mon-Fri 8 am – 5 pm PST if you are unsure whether a 1099-R is required for your outstanding loan.
Did that answer your question?
We can provide you with a copy. Please email us at support@myubiquity.com or call us at 855.401.4357, Option 2, Mon-Fri 8 am – 5 pm PST for a copy of your 1099-R .

If the request is after February 15th: ​
Please allow 2-3 business days for us to provide your electronic copy of the 1099-R form.
Did that answer your question?

Every retirement plan that held assets at any time during 2020 must file a 5500.​

botMessages.message:
The initial filing deadline to file the 2020 Form 5500 is 7/31/2021. ​

If you do not expect to be able to file by 7/31, please email us to request an extension by 7/24 and there will be no fee for the extension.
If not filed by 7/31, and we have not received your request for an extension, we will automatically file an extension for you until 10/15 with a fee of $195.

botMessages.message: If you have never registered with the Department of Labor (DOL):​
Go to efast.dol.gov ​ Select Register ​ Follow the steps to register with the DOL. Upon registration, the DOL will provide you with the information needed to electronically sign the Form 5500.
Make sure that you select “Filing Signer”, "Filing Author" and "Transmitter" for your credentials.

Please remember –​
Your User ID will start with a capital A, followed by seven digits (Example: A1234567)​
Your Pin is a 4digit number (Example: 1234)​

Late filed returns are subject to penalties from both the IRS and DOL.​
The IRS penalty for late filing of Form 5500 is $25 per day, up to a maximum of $15,000. ​ The DOL penalty for late filing can run up to $1,100 per day, with no maximum. ​
Reference Link: https://www.irs.gov/retirement-plans/401k-plan-fix-it-guide-you-havent-filed-a-form-5500

Failure or refusal to file Form 5500 can incur civil penalties up to $2,233 per day. ​
Reference Link: https://www.dol.gov/sites/dolgov/files/ebsa/about-ebsa/our-activities/resource-center/fact-sheets/adjusting-erisa-civil-monetary-penalties-for-inflati
If you identify a missed filing before the IRS or DOL, you have the option to file under the Delinquent Filer Voluntary Correction Program (DFVC).

Please contact Ubiquity at support@myubiquity.com so we can assist you in filing your delinquent Form 5500 through the DFVC program. Ubiquity’s hourly fee of $195 may apply for the preparation of form and necessary documents

This form is used by the Social Security Administration (SSA) to identify terminated employees who are entitled to distributions but haven’t taken them.
For example:
If a plan has a participant terminate during 2019 and didn’t take a distribution by December 31, 2020, that participant should be listed on the 2020 Form 8955-SSA
with an account balance and denoted with code A, indicating that the participant should be added to the SSA database.
If the participant receives their distribution in the future, they’ll be reported on the Form 8955-SSA
for the year of distribution with code D to indicate that the participant should be deleted from the SSA database.
Did that answer your question?

botDialogs.label: General questions about using Ubiquity platform.​

botMessages.message: By law, An active participant who has reached age 73 and is more than 5% owner of the company or a terminated participant who has reached age 73 as of December 31 of each calendar year and has a balance in their retirement account are required.
If the participant obtains RMD age in the current calendar year, the Ubiquity deadline to withdraw the RMD amount is extended through March 1st of the following year.
For example, if 2023 is the first year the participant has reached age 73, they could wait to request the RMD withdrawal until March 1, 2024.
Did this answer your question?

botDialogs.label: What is an RMD and who is required to take one?​

botMessages.message: A participant who has reached the age 72 (70½ if you reach 70½ before January 1, 2020). If 2021 is the first year the participant has reached age 72, the Ubiquity deadline to withdraw the amount of their RMD is extended through March 1st, 2022.
Did this answer your question?

botDialogs.label: Who needs to take an RMD?

botMessages.message: If the participant is an active employee of your company who does not own more than 5% of company shares, they may waive the RMD for the year.

Once you receive your W-2 from all of the employers that you worked for during that year, please send an email to support@myubiquity.com requesting a refund. Please include all of the following information in your email request:

1) The amount of excess.
2) Confirmation that your w-2s have not and will not be amended or adjusted.
3) The type of excess (Pre-tax or Roth).
4) Approval to process a distribution to remove the excess contribution from your account.
We ask that you log into your online account and select "Profile" at the top left and verify the address we have on file. This is where your refund check will be mailed.

Please note: A $95 processing fee is assessed for all distribution requests.
Once we have received your email request with all pertinent information, we will send you a secure link to upload legible copies of your w-2s.

botDialogs.label: How do I correct my account if I over-contributed during the year?

botMessages.message: The types of accounts that you can rollover into your plan depend on the rules and provisions set forth by your employer.

The types of accounts that you can rollover are Qualified Retirement Plans (includes, 401(k), Keogh, MEPs, and PEPs), Traditional IRA (Individual Retirement Account), SEP, 403(b) Plan, Governmental 457(b) Plan, Pension Plan, or a SIMPLE IRA.

For more information on rollovers, please visit https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-tege/rollover_chart.pdf
PLEASE NOTE: ROTH IRAs ARE NOT ELIGIBLE TO BE ROLLED OVER INTO THIS ACCOUNT.

botDialogs.label: What type of accounts can I roll into my account at Ubiquity?

botMessages.message: When you are logged into your Ubiquity account, you will need to navigate to the menu on the left hand side of the screen (top part of the screen if you are logged in on your mobile device).

From there you will choose 401(k) and then select Roll Money In from the sub-menu.
You will need to review the information in steps 1 and 2 and provide any necessary information provided their to your prior institution.

Once you have received your check, you will mail it to the address listed in step 3 of the process.
Finally, you will click on the Get Started button in step 4 and follow through the process to log your rollover.
Did that answer your question?

botDialogs.label: How do I roll money into my account at Ubiquity?

botMessages.message: To begin the process of terminating your company's retirement plan, we would need a Letter of Instruction on your company's letterhead signed by the trustee of the plan. The letter needs to include the following information:

1) Plan Name, EIN, and the reason for the termination 2) Date you intend to terminate the plan. Ubiquity must receive your request no later than 60 days prior to the intended plan termination date. 3) Date of the final payroll contributions.
This letter can be emailed to transitions@myubiquity.com.

Within 3-5 business days after submitting the letter, you will receive an email outlining the next steps in the termination process and any necessary actions required on your part to complete the process timely.
Did that answer your question?

botDialogs.label: How do I terminate my company's retirement plan?

botMessages.message: To begin the process of moving your plan to another provider, we would need you to provide a Letter of Instruction on your company's letterhead signed by the trustee of the plan.

The letter needs to indicate that you are notifying us that your plan is moving to a new provider.
Please provide the name of the new provider and any applicable contact information.
This letter can be emailed to transitions@myubiquity.com.

Within 3-5 business days of submitting the letter, you will receive an email outlining the next steps in the deconversion process and any necessary actions required on your part to complete the process timely.
Did that answer your question?
